jQuery is a fast, small, and feature-rich JavaScript library. It simplifies things like HTML document traversal and manipulation, event handling, and animation for web development. jQuery is designed to make it easier for developers to interact with and manipulate the Document Object Model (DOM) of a web page.



DOM Manipulation: jQuery simplifies the process of selecting and manipulating HTML elements on a web page. It provides a concise syntax for common tasks like changing the content of an element, adding or removing classes, handling events, and more.

Event Handling: jQuery makes it easier to handle events such as clicks, keypresses, and form submissions. Event handling with jQuery is often more concise and cross-browser compatible compared to native JavaScript.

AJAX (Asynchronous JavaScript and XML): jQuery simplifies the process of making asynchronous HTTP requests (Ajax) to the server. This allows developers to fetch data from a server without refreshing the entire page.

Animations: jQuery provides built-in functions for creating animations on a web page. This includes effects like fading in/out, sliding up/down, and custom animations.

Cross-browser Compatibility: jQuery abstracts away many of the differences between browsers, providing a consistent API that works across various browsers. This was particularly useful in the past when there were more inconsistencies between different browsers.

Plugins: jQuery has a rich ecosystem of plugins that extend its functionality. These plugins can be easily integrated into jQuery projects to add additional features and capabilities.

While jQuery was extremely popular and widely used in the past, modern web development practices have shifted toward using native JavaScript and other libraries or frameworks, such as React, Angular, or Vue.js. These modern alternatives often provide more powerful and modular approaches to building web applications. However, jQuery is still used in some legacy projects or where its simplicity is deemed beneficial.